<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1945-05-30T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1945-05-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="146" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d146">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">
                            <persName corresp="#p_THS1">Truman</persName> Papers: Telegram</note>
                        <head>No. 146 <lb/>
                            <hi rend="italic">The President’s Adviser and Assistant</hi> (<persName corresp="#p_HHL1" type="from"><hi rend="italic">Hopkins</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">President</gloss>
                            </hi><note n="1" xml:id="d146fn1">Sent by the United States Naval
                                Attaché, Moscow, via Navy channels. Cf. <ref target="#d26">document
                                    No. 26</ref>.</note>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Extracts]<note n="2" xml:id="d146fn2">For a
                                    fuller text of this message, see “The Entry of the Soviet Union
                                    Into the War Against <persName corresp="#p_J1">Japan</persName>:
                                    Military Plans, 1941–1945” (Washington, Department of Defense,
                                    processed, 1955), p. 73.</note></seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#left">
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                                <lb/>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">operational priority</hi>
                            </seg>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Moscow</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1945-05-30">30 May
                                1945</date>.</dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Personal and top secret for the eyes of the President only from <persName corresp="#p_HHL1">Hopkins</persName>.</p>
                        <p>
                            <persName corresp="#p_SMIV2">Stalin</persName> is very anxious to
                            discuss problems concerning <persName corresp="#p_J1">Japan</persName>
                            at his following [<hi rend="italic">forthcoming</hi>] conference with
                            you.</p>
                        <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                        <list>
                            <label>2.</label>
                            <item> Certain elements in <persName corresp="#p_J1">Japan</persName>
                                are putting out peace feelers[.] Therefore we should consider
                                together our joint attitude and act in concert about the surrender
                                of <persName corresp="#p_J1">Japan</persName>. …</item>
                            <label/>
                            <item rend="center">. . . . . . .</item>
                            <label>3.</label>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_SMIV2">Stalin</persName> expects that
                                    <persName corresp="#p_R4">Russia</persName> will share in the
                                actual occupation of <persName corresp="#p_J1">Japan</persName> and
                                wants an agreement with us and the British as to zones of
                                occupation.</item>
                            <label>4.</label>
                            <item>
                                <persName corresp="#p_SMIV2">Stalin</persName> also wants an
                                understanding between the Allies as to areas of operation in
                                Manchuria and China.</item>
                        </list>
                        <p rend="center">. . . . . . .</p>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>